segments.text: about the homecoming or the the reception or the lack of reception to receive uh no but i'm not sure that i ever expected one i had spent the previous 12 to 15 years going overseas and coming back home and you know it's a solitary thing coming in by myself going out by myself i never really expect anybody to have a band waiting for me
Going to Vietnam was just another two-year overseas, and coming back, coming home again.
I didn't expect a band.
It wasn't all that kind of a glory thing to me.
It was a job to do, a job that I had agreed to do as part of my career.
That's the only thing I looked at.
It was somewhere to go to do the job, and I'd come back.
If I had to go again, I went again.
But I don't think that I approached it with a...
glory after the fact that some of our speakers have said they expected on their return.
I don't know how anybody realistically could look at war as something where it was a glorious thing to get into.
Perhaps it's because they didn't have the training.
They've seen a lot of movies and films.
That's great.
You know the guy's going to get up and walk away after the film's over with.
That's not a realistic concept of what war is.
If you've been training for war most of your life, you don't have that concept.
I never expected any big parade or anything.
I never felt rejected by the society.
I never had any real derogatory comments directed at me.
One of our speakers said he was sped up on whatever.
I just crossed the country several times, going to Vietnam, coming back to Vietnam in my uniform.
I never had anybody say anything to me.
And I think I probably mingled with the same people those guys did coming in and out of San Francisco and California and up there.
So I don't think we were that much rejected.
Nobody just paid any attention to us.
If you're looking for a big parade, obviously you can feel rejected.
It wasn't my idea.
I wanted to get off the plane and go home.
OK.
I don't know if you, were you watching the news in 1975 when Saigon fell?
And if so, or even if not, how did you, did you feel really like you just wasted your time there?
How'd that make you feel?
Oh, I watched it.
The only thing that I
could say about it.
Well, it happened.
I knew it probably would.
I didn't have any real doubts that they could hold out if we decided to pull out when Nixon started talking an honorable piece and get us out and get me settled among themselves.
It was pretty much a foregone conclusion among most of us that had been there that if they got out peaceably, that it wouldn't last six months.
Within six months, they'd either be swamped or they'd be going to war again.
So we didn't see anything really different from what we had suspected once we decided we were going to get out of there.
I personally couldn't see how the Vietnamese could stand up to them if they hadn't been able to do it all that time.
With us there, they certainly wouldn't be able to do it with us out there.
It was just a matter of he came sooner or not.
I thought he would.
I didn't feel any evil.
Regrets about it.
I certainly didn't feel that we'd spend our time here for nothing.
We did what we set out to do during the time that we were there.
If that was our goal, then we accomplished our goal.
But it didn't make me feel like we had been defeated by any means or that we'd been betrayed or anything else.
It was simply the outcome.
It was a logical outcome the way we were headed.
You want to get emotionally tied up into it, and you probably could feel that you were kind of betrayed for the time you spent over there, but I don't know.
I never looked at it as an emotional thing.
I knew there was another job to do.
I went to do the job.
I came home, but I had to go back and do the job again.
Never any real emotion tied up for that place.
I could have cared less one way or the other which way it went.
But when I was told to go there and do a job, I went there and did the job.
That's the only way I would have cared.
I would say that in personal encounter with the Vietnamese, I knew after my first tour there that we were fighting sort of a losing battle.
The Vietnamese themselves, if they would ever talk to you,
didn't really care whether it was BC or Arvin running the country.
So long as somebody was stabilized, they only have to contend with one government.
So here they are in the middle of everything.
Put up with BC when they were there, and put up with Arvin when they were controlling the area, and they didn't care.
It was totally immaterial for the little guy out in the village.
And a lot of them couldn't tell you anything in the world about what was going on outside their own village.
As far as Saigon, they didn't know who or what or when.
They didn't care.
It didn't affect them, except they had to pay taxes to the Arvin, and they turned around and paid taxes to VC when they came through the collection.
Like I said, if you could get one of them to talk to you, there was no Arvin around.
He'd tell you, why don't y'all go home?
And one of these two people decide who's going to be in charge and who'll get on with their life.
That was pretty much the thing that I could get from an average guy out there on the farm.
It didn't really surprise me when it went out there.
Dr. Anderson in class has talked about his trip back to Vietnam, and he's planning to go again.
Would you be interested at all in ever going back, or say as a tourist?
No.
I don't.
You don't feel any attachment or anything?
I have no attachment there.
If it were as a tourist and there was something they could offer me, it would be worthwhile to see.
I might go as a tourist to see something I might have missed when I wasn't there.
But I don't know of anything in Vietnam that I would care to go back to see.
I saw a good deal of it while I was there.
Probably a closer perspective than most tourists will ever get to see it.
And certainly
a better perspective of it than most GIs who went over and worked with pure American units.
Most of those never got to see much more than the base they were stationed at or the jungle they were trooping around in, and that's not a very good view of it.
With the advisory we got out, there was very little that I didn't know about my own province, very little that I hadn't seen or been into.
a couple of the bordering provinces and up and around Saigon.
I made a few trips around the country to see what it looked like, visit with other teams to see how they were doing and what they were doing that we might incorporate into our effects.
I probably got to see more of Vietnam than any tourist will ever get to see.
I have no feeling about going back there.
There's nobody there.
I want to see how it turned out, as I know pretty much how it turned out.
I haven't talked to them before I left.
I knew pretty much what was going on there.
I don't care if I can see them.
If you get down to the local level, you find that life hasn't changed very much at all.
Maybe a little bit more hungry and a little bit less...
well-fed or taken care of, but I don't think overall the peasant's life changed a great deal.
Harder to be certain.
One last hypothetical question here.
After Ted, you were saying, do you think if we stepped up our presence there and say, had we gone ahead and won, had there been no negative view in the media and had it been okay?
Even if we had won, do you think that would have just
you know, quashed the will of the North Vietnamese, or would there have been another uprising, you think?

Well, if you're going on the assumption that we could have achieved a peace where the country would have remained divided, if that's what you're asking, then I don't think a lasting peace could have been established on that basis.
The sole purpose of the North was to reunite the country.
under one government.
Given that, they might have accepted a temporary truce or peace because of their losses or whatever that we could have inflicted upon them if they did that.
I think it probably would have been a temporary thing.
You might wind up with a situation like you have in Korea, where since 1953, we've been a divided country there, and the fighting has been off and on.
And even today, they're still fighting here.
It might have evolved into something like that, but I don't think there would ever have been any real true peace.
And I think probably it would not have stabilized my career because the North Koreans were much, much more aggressive about reuniting the country than the North Koreans were.
So it may have stabilized for a year, maybe two or three, and I think people would turn around and start holding it over again.
But we would never really have gotten rid of the VC

whatever academy still down in the south they've still been in place still working for a different form of government if they could have achieved a government where you had equal representation between bc and normal people maybe maybe it might have stabilized but that didn't work too well in layoffs either where they established any coalition government it fell apart coalition governments are not the answer
One side of it is a bet on having the whole country under their control, but I don't see how you're going to alter that.
You may delay it, but you won't alter it until you eventually start over again.
It's like a comparison to North Korea.
It's like sitting on top of a bomb over there with a short fuse, and the fuse is burning.
When is it going to explode again?
The last time I was over there, this was after Vietnam.
We were close to going back to war there.
Something as simple as a matter of cutting down a tree.
I don't know if you can look it up, but there was an incident where an American officer got killed in the DMZ by North Korean troops.
And all they were trying to do was cut down a tree and kill him.
And we were on DEFCON 1, which was defensive condition one.
The only thing that was left was simply blow one more whistle and we were over again.
And they sent people in there.
armed to cut down a tree.
Had they been fired upon, we would have been at war.
Very simple as that.
It was kind of a powder keg.
I think we would have wound up with essentially the same situation in Vietnam if they had achieved another peace.
How long it would have lasted is a conjecture.
But I don't think it would have lasted, not like Korea has.
Okay, I don't have any further questions.
Do you have anything else to add?
No, not particularly.
I think it was an experience, but on the whole, I never really viewed it as going anywhere.
It was just simply part of the job, but I couldn't see it being productive.
You know, like World War I, World War II, when we achieved a solution by arms, I could not see it reaching that degree.
It was part of the job.
I did it.
That's what I signed on to do.
Okay.
Well, that concludes our interview.
Thank you, Mr. Price.
